postcontent:
Up for sale is a kimber custom crimson carry ii. It is a full size 1911. I bought this new from shoot straight in apopka, fl/october 2012 and have the bill of sale from that. This kimber began its life as a custom crimson carry ii. That is what is still inscribed on the slide. I then decided to change it and sent it to kimber to have the frame refinished to their dark earth. They also installed all black parts including an ambidextrous safety. I have all the paperwork from kimber showing what they did. When it returned I sold the rosewood crimson trace grips it originally came with and put on the crimson trace digital camo grips. It comes with a battery installed, an extra battery, the laser sighting tool and a small cloth on a handle to clean the laser itself when it gets dirty. I had trijicon night sights installed (yellow rear, green front) I finished it off with an STI trigger and STI main spring plug. The finished product is a clone of the kimber covert ii but (in my opinion) with a better trigger and night sights. Ive never had an issue with the gun for the short time ive had it. It is a full size 1911 and was my edc gun. Also included are all the grey parts it originally came with that kimber switched out to black and one kimber 1911 mag. It has been frog lubed its entire life (personal preference I know) I can give you any other info you need on it and/or pictures you may want, if interested.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Stevens 77A 12 gauge pump shotgun
postcontent:
Stevens 77A shotgun - 12 gauge pump action with 5+1 capacity, 26" barrel, appears to have been made around 1954, nice original wood and red recoil pad, lots of finish wear, but no rust.  Old school Polychoke on the end that allows you to twist to adjust the full range of all chokes. 

It was originally purchased as a fixer-upper - it fires fine every time, but the cartridge stop mechanism that keeps the shells in the magazine tube is worn and either needs to be adjusted or replaced in order to keep the shells from all trying to come out with each pump.  Pretty easy fix, but my family has grown and I don't have time to work on this project. 

The other thing that I read about folks doing is lopping off part of the barrel to convert it to a replica of the Stevens 77E, a popular riot/battle shotgun used during the Vietnam War.  I had also thought about doing this project, but again, my growing family prevents me from dedicating time to projects like this one.

Asking $125 for a face-to-face transaction in Waco area to Texas residents eligible to own firearms.  Bill of sale required.  I sometimes travel to Temple for work or Austin, Dallas, Houston to visit family, so I could consider transactions there based on my travel schedule.  This would make a great project shotgun for someone doing the Vietnam era reproduction or for a teenager's first hunting shotgun.

title: For Trade:  Ruger SP101 .357 3" Spurless
postcontent:
*For the reading-challenged: I WILL NOT TRADE THIS GUN FOR PAPER, A.K.A "CASH". NO CASH FOR THIS GUN.

This magnum came into my life brand new in early 1992 (made in 1991), as my first handgun. During the first 10 years or so, it was my primary carry gun, and saw a lot of action. Primarily, I fired 38Spl, because I was never very good with magnums in it.

Since then, it has mostly chilled in various night stands and storage rooms, with occasional trips to the range, or a run around town. I would estimate the round count is no more than 5k - 99% of it was 38Spl.

The hammer was bobbed early in its life, back when Ruger didn't make a spurless SP at all. (In 3" they still don't!) I think the gunsmith contoured it very nicely to preserve as much hammer mass and thickness as possible.

Just recently, I had the HiViz sight put on it, which works great. The springs are all original, and over the years, the action has become lighter and smoother with use, but not as light as Wolff.

At some point, the little pin Ruger gave to use for disassembly got away, but I always liked using a little nail more for that anyway.

Accessories included:
*The holster is a custom-fit Milt Sparks "Summer Special" IWB. 
*The speedloaders are Safariland Comp I push-release, which are PERFECT for quick reloads under stress... 
*The holders are also Safariland Split-Six, and are like new.
*The spare grip is Hogue Monogrip.
*Original manual.
*AceCase soft pistol case. (Not shown in the pics) Made in USA The original box was cardboard back then, and I discarded it. 
More pics availabe upon request. 

The 271 rounds of ammo includes:
*6 Silver Glasers 38Spl+P
*35 Federal Hi-Shok 125gr HP 357Mag
*15 Federal HP 357Mag of unknown weight
*200 of Georgia Arms 38Spl 158gr Copper-Plated-SWC (second box not shown)
*15 Corbon 38Spl+P+ 115gr (These are the very hot 38 +P+ loads Corbon used to make in the 90's. The current ones are not that hot. It's almost a magnum round.)

This excellent revolver never failed me, and means a lot to me for sentimental, personal reasons. However, I under-utilize its full magnum potential, have too many guns, want to try new ones, and don't like to form attachments to things. So, it's time to let this trusty friend move on to new adventures...

title: For Sale:  Spanish Star 30MI Miltary/Police Full Size Hi Capacity  9mm Automatic
location: SE Baton Rouge Near I12, Louisiana, United States
postcontent: This is a nice used (Import) Star 30MI 9mm(Luger) High Capacity Automatic.The Barrel is 4.7 inches long. Total length is 8.1 inches. The magazine has a 15 round capacity. Ten round magazines can be used also. Total weight unloaded is 2.5 pounds. The Orginal Finish is about 90%. The Bore is excellent. One Grip Panel shows extentive wear at the bottom. The Star 30MI had been developed and manufactured in Spain by Star Bonifacio Echeverria SA company. The Star 30M appeared in 1990 and had been adopted as a service pistol by the Spanish army and police, as well as by Peruvian police. Technically, the Star 30MI is an updated version of the earlier Star 28M pistol. Star 30MI is a recoil operated, locked breech pistol, that uses Browning-designed, linkless locking (High Power-type), with two lugs on the barrel and shaped cam under the chamber that interacts with slide stop axis iside the frame. Star 30MI features double action trigger with slide mounted ambidextrous safety that locks firing ping only, leaving trigger and hammer unaffected in "safety on" position, thus allowing the gun to be "dry fired" (however, this is unsafe and is not recommended). Star 30MI also features magazine safety, that disables firing when magazine in not in position. Another safety feature is a loaded chamber indicator. Star 30MI features internal slide rails (like the SIG P-210 or CZ-75). The frame and slide are made from steel (the aluminium-alloy frame version of the Star 30MI is called Star 30PK and is somewhat lighter, as one can expect). The front sight is fixed, the rear sight is dovetailed and thus can be ajusted for windage. The Star 30MI is a reliable, accurate pistol and can be used for self defense and Home Protection.

title: For Sale:  Spanish Astra 400 9mm Largo w/Holster Extra Mag
location: SE Baton Rouge near Airline Hwy and I12, Louisiana, United States
postcontent: This is a good condition Astra 400 Pistol with Holster and extra magazine. The serial number is 77646 indicating it was manufactured in the 1937-1938 time period. Type: Single Action Chamber: mod.400: 9x23mm (9mm Largo or 9mm Steyr), 9x19mm Luger/Parabellum, 9x20mm Browning long (mod.600 - 9x19mm Luger/Parabellum only) Weight loaded: 1140 g (1080 g) Length: 225 mm (205 mm) Barrel length: 150 mm (135 mm) Capacity: 8 rounds The "Astra" trademark belongs to the "Societa Unceta and compania" company (current name Astra-Unceta y Cia) , located in the Guernica, Spain. The Astra mod. 400 pistol first appeared in the early 1920s and had been adopted by the Spain Military in 1921. This pistol was also widely exported to many countries, includint the Hitlers' Germany, that purchased the mod. 400 pistols for its army. The production of the mod.400 had been completed in 1950. Technically, the mod.400 is a blowback operated, hammer fired, single action semiautomatic pistol. It was chambered primary for 9mm Largo (9x23mm Bergmann-Bayard) cartridge but chamber and magazine dimensions allowed to load and fire other 9mm cartridges, such as 9x23mm Steyr, 9x20mm Browning long, 9x19mm Luger/Parabellum, offering almost unprecendent versatility. The recoil spring is located around the barrel. The gun featured no manual safeties. One automatic safety is located at the rear of the grip and locks sear when gun does not gripped by the shooter properly; another, internal safety, disconets the trigger bar from the sear when gun is off the battery (slide does not closed completely). The slide stop is located at the left side of the frame. Thanks to the long barrel and heavy weight, the gun was comfortable to fire and showed good acuuracy.
